; body-state.form — collapse the body's live signals into one inspectable state a dashboard can show.
;
; THE ASK (device-heartbeat.form, OBSERVABILITY lane):
;   "running in a way I can SEE what it is doing, what state it is in, which organs are active,
;    surprise events, infer error (core for learning)."
;
;   device-heartbeat.form lane-sorted that ask: observability is a CARRIER (the live view); the things
;   it shows are BODY, mostly already proven. This recipe is that carrier surface, runnable — the fold
;   that gathers the already-proven live signals into one readable STATE cell the dashboard renders.
;   It computes nothing new; it makes the body's own answer legible at a glance.
;
; THE SHAPE  (runnable: form-stdlib/body-state.fk · proven: tests/body-state-band.fk -> 127)
;
;   A state = (list organs-active present-peers surprise-count error-count sample-count) — five plain
;   non-negative ints, one frame of the body's vitals:
;
;   ACCESSORS  bs-organs / bs-peers / bs-surprises / bs-errors / bs-samples — pull each count out (nth).
;
;   bs-alive?       peers > 0 — is anyone on the mesh? self counts as 1, so present means alive. The
;                   peers come from hb-present? over received beacons (device-heartbeat).
;   bs-busy-organs? organs >= min — enough senses live to call the body perceiving. Organs come straight
;                   from hb-organs / hb-organ-active? per device (device-heartbeat).
;   bs-surprised?   surprises > 0 — something did not fit; a thing for the view to highlight. Surprises
;                   are novelty.fk readings below the recognition floor / anomaly-band outside-band.
;   bs-learning?    samples > errors — net-learning, more right than wrong so far. Errors are the
;                   prediction misses (sequence-predictor PREDICT, then predicted != actual, counted by
;                   drift-detect.fk, graded by self-grounding-classifier.fk). The TRUE learning signal is
;                   error-count FALLING, but that is invisible in one snapshot — so this reads net, a
;                   proven-COUNT GATE, not a ratio (no division, per AUTHORING's count-gate rule).
;
; HOW IT COMPOSES THE SPINE — it invents no signal, it folds existing ones:
;   organs   <- device-heartbeat.fk (hb-organs / hb-organ-active?)
;   peers    <- device-heartbeat.fk (hb-present? over beacons)
;   surprises<- novelty.fk (below-floor) + anomaly-band.fk (outside-band)
;   errors   <- sequence-predictor.fk (predict) + drift-detect.fk (predicted != actual count)
;   samples  <- the graded denominator self-grounding-classifier.fk already tracks
;   The band passes the counts directly (self-contained — it preludes only body-state.fk + core), but
;   in the live system those numbers arrive from the kin recipes above. This is the dashboard's
;   framebuffer: the recipes upstream make the signals real, this fold makes them readable.
;
; ── HONEST LANE ──
;   A state is ONE FRAME — a snapshot, not a trend. bs-learning? is therefore deliberately crude: it
;   reads "net right" (samples > errors), not "improving." Whether error-count is actually FALLING over
;   time needs a sequence of frames (drift-detect over a window), which this single-frame fold cannot
;   see and does not claim. The view shows the present vitals honestly; the trend lives elsewhere.
;
; KIN: device-heartbeat.form (organs + present-peers — the heartbeat this state reads) · novelty.form +
;   anomaly-band.form (the surprises it counts) · drift-detect.form + sequence-predictor (the inference-
;   errors it counts) · self-grounding-perception.form (the graded samples) · recognition-router.form
;   (the same band trick — consume a bare ge/gt inside `if`, never via eq, so kernels agree) ·
;   lc-honest-lane (one frame claims only what one frame can see).
;
; LINEAGE: device-heartbeat.form named observability as a carrier over signals the body already proves;
;   this is that carrier's read — the smallest state a human (or the Mac/app dashboard) needs to answer
;   "what is it doing, who is here, did something surprise it, is it net-learning?" in a single glance.
